brieflydescribe: Story of a mother with three children who became homeless through no fault of their own. It account for why the eviction occured and takes us through the next few months of her desperate search for affordable housing and trying to find a place to sleep each night. She eventually find help from her best friend but really it is only a temporary solution
thoughtsfeels: For story was very personal but it did leave out some details. It made no mention, other than fixed income, of the mothers salary and what she had available in terms of renatl money. It also does not mention the type of property she was looking for or the avenues she explored, other than Craigs list, to secure accomodation
whydonate: I feel that its good to donate but also that I should be rewarded for giving up my time with the study. A 50:50 compromise seemed like a good option, I feel positive about it
otherissues: None the process was smooth and interesting
comments: I think that although the story did lack certain facts it does highlight homelessness can happen to almost anyone

brieflydescribe: The whole thing happened the week of July 4. Although my rent had been faithfully paid throughout my entire tenancy, the owners of the town home I had been renting for the past three years had not paid their mortgage in at least a third of that time. After a series of frantic phone calls (property management company, Real Estate Commission, and the sheriff's department), I had determined a few unfortunate things. Because the owner - knowing of this impending doom - had delayed signing my new lease, I had little to no protection.

brieflydescribe: A single mother of 3 children became homeless when the owner of the townhouse she rented did not pay the mortgage and lost it. The children went to stay with relatives for a week but ended up being there a month. The mother ran the gamut of friends & family trying to find a safe place for her and her children. In the end an old school friend and her husband allowed them all to stay in their spare room . A move that renewed the mothers faith in people.
thoughtsfeels: I have been there. Almost the only difference was that I had 2 children and it didnt last quite so long. I was also pregnant and petrified. It lasted a month but it changed me and it took a very long time before I began to feel secure again. I now own my own home and in many ways it was being homeless that drove me to working hard until I could buy a home. My heart aches for this mother. I wish I could help her
whydonate: I feel 1/2 is fair. I donate to several charities but I am certainly not rich so this seems a fair way to decide.

brieflydescribe: Person with 3 children were renting a home, but the owner of that home wasn't able to pay the lease so the person with 3 children were also kicked out. The person with the 3 children then became homeless and was borrowing places to stay at from relatives, friends, and strangers, while desperately looking for a new home.
thoughtsfeels: The story showed the warmth and kindness shown towards people in times of need and gives me hope in humanity.
whydonate: I didn't donate, because I am currently in a situation where I want all the money I could get. Although my family and relatives have a good amount of money, I would feel ashamed if I relied too heavily on them.

brieflydescribe: A woman with three children gets evicted from her home. She then struggles to find a place to live while her kids are with their grandparents in Texas. The woman proceeds from city to city, sleeping on the couches of friends and relatives, until she is able to settle down with an old friend from college.
thoughtsfeels: I honestly cannot sympathize with the protagonist. Of course we don't know the whole story, but my main concern is why would she have three kids if she wasn't able to support them. Also, she tends to complain about things a lot, such as her sisters lack of air conditioning. It bothers me that she disrupts the lives of people around her, but then complains that their accomodations are not good enough.
whydonate: Because if I had a lot of money to donate I wouldn't be online doing surveys for small change.

brieflydescribe: The author of the story was evicted from their home due to non-payment of the mortgage by the landlords. They attempted to find a new place to live for themselves and their three children, resorting to friends, relatives and parents for temporary accommodation while they searched. Eventually, they were able to move in with a friend from college, giving some stability to their family as the school year started.
thoughtsfeels: The description of the panic that sets in as the author realizes they have nowhere to live, and the ensuing frantic search for a home, is very similar to what friends of mine have gone through. The author's description of how they got by without permanent accommodation made me wonder if I had done as much as I could to help my friends when this happened. I was relieved that the author was eventually able to find somewhere to stay, but I realize that many other people will not. This article made it easier to empathize with their situation.
whydonate: I support a number of charitable organizations, including Habitat for Humanity. I am happy for them to have a portion of my payment for this exercise, but do not feel an obligation for them to receive all of it.
comments: This study was presented much more thoughtfully than many other surveys. I particularly enjoyed the format of the interactive story at the beginning. The topic is one that interests me, and that has affected some good friends of mine.

brieflydescribe: A single mother and her three children became homeless as their landlord had not paid his mortgage. Whilst her children were at their grandparents she had to pack up and put things in storage. She had to rely on her family and friends to put her them up. She could not find decent affordable housing and they are now temporarily living with an old college friend and her husband and new baby.
thoughtsfeels: I feel sympathy for her and her children, and hope she soon found permanent accommodation. I feel angry with the system for letting her down, and think she should have been entitled to more support. I think this must have happened in the US rather than the UK because whilst the British system is far from perfect the local councils would have had a legal responsibility to ensure they were housed.
whydonate: Because what haven't got I won't miss, and it will do far more for the charity than it will for me.

brieflydescribe: A woman and her children were evicted from their apartment because the landlord had lost the apartment building through foreclosure. Since she had not signed a lease, the nedw owner was under no obligation to rent the apartment to her. She looked diligently for a new place to live to no avail. After staying at several places temporarily and even sleeping in her car for a while, her best friend provided her and her children with a room in their two-bedroom apartment to stay while she looked for a new place to live.
thoughtsfeels: The story was extremely well written. I got a vivid picture of what she was going through and could empathize with her.
whydonate: I don't like feeling manipulated. If you and your university want to make a charitable donation to a worthwhile cause, then do so directly. People who do these surveys (including me) do them because they need the money, and your survey is underpaid even when including the bonus. Think about it - would you work for $2.00/hr? I have a limited budget, and I do include charitable donations in that budget, and I have already decided which charities I will contribute to this year.

brieflydescribe: A person with two children gets evicted and ends up homeless, having nowhere to turn that is accommodating, gets help from strangers and poor people and finally ends up at her friend's place.
thoughtsfeels: I have been put on the street by the government. I got more help from strangers and people who had nothing than from people earning money to help me. I didn't have a car and ended up at (most times) staying with one of the few fellows I knew I had to sleep with. They usually had no food so I went to the Shepherd's of Good Hope for meals and the centre 454 drop in to do my laundry and have a shower if I had slept outside on the canal and hidden from the NRTC. I live in Canada so this probably would not happen like it was explained in the story, there are shelters for women and children. Nice one's too!
whydonate: I enjoy sharing and giving. I need half and so does Habitat for Humanity.
otherissues: It put me in mind of what I went through. I had no car but I didn't have children living with me.
comments: I used to have to live day to day, wondering where I was going to eat, sleep, look for bus fare etc. It is so hard for someone that has to live out of a bag or a car, they need routine, especially with children and social services should have helped them.

brieflydescribe: A single mother of three became homeless after she was evicted from her home because her landlord failed to pay the mortgage on it even though she always paid the rent on it. She spent months looking for somewhere else to rent but couldn't find anywhere because the market was too competitive. Then a friend took the four of them in despite being married with a baby and living in a 2 bedroom apartment.
thoughtsfeels: I didn't know America had such a housing crisis. I can't imagine what it would be like to be living as one of 7 in a 2 bed apartment. I can't imagine thinking of that as a solution. It was very unfair that she suffered so much for something that was not her fault. Being asked about your housing situation every week gets very old very quickly, and my experience of that was merely about immensely delayed completion (7 months), and my parents made me very welcome.
whydonate: Advertised payment on get-paid.com is 44 coins, which amounts to 8.8 cents. Near the beginning of the survey it says I'll get 20 cents. In reality I'll get 14% more than 8.8 cents because I'll get a level bonus for being in level 10. So assuming the dollar is subject to the same calculation, I would rather give a dollar to a worthy cause than receive about 50 cents myself. It just makes more sense that I would get the biggest reward I can for a survey, even if the reward doesn't go to me. It seems more constructive and a better use of my time.

thoughtsfeels: I just read a book about homelessness, and this was equally graphic. I feel terrible for the woman and her children. whydonate: I believe other people need money, but I also need money. If I didn't need money, I wouldn't be spending my spare time taking surveys that earn me only pennies.

brieflydescribe: A woman was bound to become homeless due to her landlords not keeping up with their mortgage expenses. She sent her three children away to a family reunion while she tried to figure out what to do. She weighed options between family members, friends, and strangers on who could help her.
thoughtsfeels: It was very heartfelt. I have been in a situation where I was homeless for about a month. I stayed with strangers and even one night at a motel after being kicked out by my ex boyfriend's mother. I was doing my best trying to earn income by babysitting. She was upset with me because I didn't return to school. I was not able to go back to college at that time because I didn't have the funds. She just wouldn't understand that. Finally, my ex boyfriend had some luck and found a job at Walmart. We were still staying with strangers for a while, but it allowed us to finally look for places even more now that there was more income coming in. This story is very relevant to me, although, I don't have any kids. I am always empathetic to people in this situation.
whydonate: I think every little bit helps. I would rather donate something, than nothing at all.
comments: I was happy to read this story as it is a reminder that you can always fall to the bottom even if not the fault of your own.

brieflydescribe: A woman, through no fault of her own, found herself homeless when she was evicted from her apartment. Her three children went to live with their grandparents, while she looked for a permanent place to live. She spent a few days in different homes, but each one had its issues. She even slept some days in her car.
thoughtsfeels: Of course I found sympathy for the woman. It was interesting to read things from her point of view. I had never really thought of such a situation from the point of view of the homeless person, nor the events that got her into that situation. I was glad that her children were safe while she went about the very difficult task of finding a new home. I suppose that this experience would jade her, but I found her attitude a bit rude and sarcastic sometimes. For example the fact that her sister's house was hot, did not mean that that was not a place she could stay for a while. Her sister was obviously living in those conditions.
whydonate: If the purpose of the survey was to make us aware of homelessness and how it can happen to anybody through no fault of their own, then it makes sense to donate the money to that cause. I am trying to earn extra money doing surveys for my own reasons, but it does not seem as important at this moment.
comments: Thank you for the thought provoking study so early in the morning!

brieflydescribe: Guy lost his dwelling because the owners of said dwelling defaulted on their mortgage payments. Guy and three kids move around from place to place. They settle on Guy's best friend apartment thanks to her generosity.
thoughtsfeels: Initially, I felt as much empathy for this man as one could possibly feel. His eviction was clearly not his fault. Learning that he did not demand sufficient protection from his landlords (in legal form) makes me think that this man is intellectually ill equipped to deal with the world. That shortened the empathy. As the text unfolded, I kept asking myself why this man does not rent another place and comes up with excuse after excuse for not doing what everybody else does (find a home that fits their budget)? My final impression is that this man shows parasitical traits, that attempting any solution that does not entail any form of payment (like helping his brother, sister, mother or best friend with rent or mortgage) is first and foremost in his mind. In the end I only felt sorry for his children, but none for him.
whydonate: I chose to donate nothing. I like to choose my own charities, according to my own sense of priorities, and whether I find that a particular institution is politically motivated or not, and in what way does that motivation show. I do not give to charities that do not meet my minimum standards of priority and it does political motivations and allegiances.
storyoff_what: I think I recall narrative inconsistencies but gave it no thought, as it did not compromise what the goal of the text was, and it did not affect my opinion, which by that point was beginning to congeal.
comments: If you have contact with the gentleman in question, please tell him that Craigslist is a decent place to find an apartment.

brieflydescribe: A single mother of three lost her home because her landlords defaulted on their mortgage. Because of the influx of renters after the housing market collapsed (even with the market recovery), affordable housing was sparse and most landlords didn't want to consider her due to her family and single fixed income. The woman and her family bounced around from various family members and friends, and finally found a place to live due to the kindness of one of her college friends.
thoughtsfeels: I really felt bad for this woman trying to raise a family of three on her own while trying to look for a place to live (I may be single, but I know the feeling of being unable to find affordable housing all too well). It's a very sad testament to the housing crisis we're still in -- despite all the market indicators that say we're past it now -- and how few people are willing to actually HELP someone in need.
whydonate: The story really made me think about people struggling with homelessness. As much as I would like to have had the full bonus payment, I realized it would be no hardship for me to give half of what I would have received to help people in need.
otherissues: I didn't encounter any issues with the survey.
comments: Thank you for acknowledging and presenting the issues people have with finding affordable housing.

brieflydescribe: Someone became homeless suddenly and had to move out of their house, due to their landlord not paying tax or renewing the lease. They had to pack their belongings and live in their car for a while, and their children got to stay at the person's parents' home in Texas for a month. After this, they all had to live in different places, in friends' and family members' homes, but the school year was about to start, and this lifestyle couldn't continue, but the family managed to find a place with the author's friend from college and her husband.
thoughtsfeels: I have been in similar situations to the author, but fortunately, I have no children. I believe that this is a very unfair situation, as the landlord was clearly at fault, and it seems as if the tenant's life has been seriously messed up. The story makes no mention of what happened to their job once they moved out.
whydonate: I expected to get one dollar from completing this survey, but if there is an option to donate, that's fine too. I am not cash rich at the moment, which is why I'm doing so many surveys, and I am keeping 50% of the dollar as a result. (I can cash out my Crowdflower account now, and that will go towards the deposit on my new apartment, believe it or not.)
Occupation_otherwhat: Student in a full time internship.
storyoff_what: The story seemed a bit jumpy, and there was no mention of what happened to the author's job after the first week. It seemed that there was no mention of the cost of living, the children just reappeared. I am surprised that what happened was legal.
otherissues: It was not initially clear that there was a link at the bottom of the page where it said to return to the survey.

brieflydescribe: A single parent was forced out of his home because of the owner not paying the rent. He goes homeless for a spell while he juggles work and parenting. He finds a solution at a best friend's residence.
thoughtsfeels: The story is sad, and it felt very real, but I kept wondering if there were any social assistance programs or legal counsel this man would have been able to seek for damages / reparation. I also thought that some of his negative responses to the choices of where to stay were not good enough reasons to leave that should/could have been worked out in light of his dire circumstances.
whydonate: I earn my living working from home, so this is my source of income participating in surveys like these. After I have accounted for my necessities, I then look at my surplus, if any, and decide on annual donations to charities of my choice.
storyoff_what: The choices felt restrictive, and more like blind guessing
otherissues: Just to clarify my illogical comment; I felt like the characters were not introduced to make good decisions on where to go. I felt like I was flipping a coin because I had no background information to go on. I'm not sure if this study found our order of choices important, but I wanted to point that out.
comments: Some of the review questions were difficult to recall because they focused on details I didn't think were important to the story.

brieflydescribe: Notice to quit the family home within 4 days. Hapless search for a new home. Many unhelpful suggestions, but a few helpful friends and parents.

whydonate: The USA is a cruel place, insofar as it's social safety net is broken and has stayed broken for at least the last 50 years. I don't really know why this happens, but guess it is something to do with an inadequate distribution of wealth. The US school system also seems to me to be inadequate at preparing kids for the real world, which is why so many join the military. The knock-on effect of that being un-called-for intervention in countries overseas that don't want or need US 'help', which invariably results in wide scale destruction and mass murder. Disgusting.
otherissues: If one decides to go and live in the not so 'Good 'ol US of A, then one had better beware how it fails it's people!

The only saving grace was her dependable old car and a good friend from college and her husband that had a new baby took her and kids in and she felt for the first time in months that she had a home with some normalcy.
thoughtsfeels: I found myself totally involved with this woman's plight, how hard it must have been to not have a home and to exhaust all avenues only to come to a dead end. It made it even harder with 3 children that depended on her. I could envision myself in her place and felt so helpless in listening to her story. brieflydescribe: The women rented her home and got kicked out because the owner didn't pay their mortgage, leaving her homeless with three kids. She struggled to find a new place to live and ended up staying with friends and family intermittently, leading to great uncertainty in her and her childrens' life. Various family members tried to help but something didn't work with each (allergic to cats, no ac) and coworkers and friends offered useless suggestions or avoided her. However, she became more grateful for what she did have like a reliable car and a best friend who stepped up and let her stay with them.
thoughtsfeels: While most of us like to think we'd never be homeless, homelessness can happen to most people given the right circumstances. While this women had friends to rely on, not everyone does, emphasizing the importance of shelters and other aid systems. I think the story emphasizes the uncertainty this can cause, particularly in the lives of children. Ultimately, high cost of housing is a factor in most US cities and is something as a society that has to be addressed.
whydonate: I contribute to Habitat to Humanity in other ways such as shopping at the Habitat to Humanity store.

brieflydescribe: It's about a women who became homeless with her three kids. She had been evicted from her townhome, due to the negligence of her landlord, who was not paying mortgage on the property, which led to this woman not signing a new lease, and thus being left with no sort of protection. She lived from sofa to sofa with her kids, utilizing friends and family to get through, before finally finding a friend to stay with until she can find a place of her own.
thoughtsfeels: It sucks for many reasons, one, it's a story too often told for a country that harbors such wealth, two, where was the father in all of this? But, this person was lucky to have friends and family that were eager to help out, there are so many who don't have such safety nets, and every day their very existence is criminalized, from the prohibiting of sleeping in public places, to aggressive policing for public urination, etc. It sucks.
whydonate: I'm homeless. I do surveys at the local library daily, struggling to make enough to get Target eGift card or two just to get food. Unlike the lady in the story, I don't have a family to take me in, or a car to sleep in. I sleep out on the street, and I'm treated like a criminal everywhere I go, that's why I spoke about the criminalization of homelessness earlier. I know firsthand. I've been homeless for six years, and nothing is getting better for me. So, yeah, Life sucks, and then you die. I go to sleep at night focusing on the dying part of that saying, hoping that some night I'll close my eyes and never open them again, but six years later, I'm still waking up and fewer and fewer opportunities are available to me.

brieflydescribe: This story described what happened to a single parent and their three kids when the parent was unexpectedly but suddenly evicted. The parent faced a lot of stress and worry trying to find affordable housing for the family. Eventually, a kind friend was able to take in the family and provide some stability while they continued to search for a home.
thoughtsfeels: While being homeless must be a difficult struggle for anyone, this story really made me think of how difficult it would be for someone who had school-age children. The story also made me realize how much the homeless situation must have affected the parent's job performance, just because they were constantly anxious and stressed from not having a permanent home.
whydonate: I decided on 50% because I felt like it was a good balance between keeping the entire extra $1 and using part of it to benefit others.

brieflydescribe: A person was left homeless after receiving an eviction notice due to the landlord not paying the mortgage on the property. This person and his/her children then had to spend several months without a stable home while searching for a permanent place to live. Throughout this period, both friends and family members accommodated them in their homes thus providing much needed relief, hospitality, and generosity, which was much appreciated by the main character of the story as evidenced by the concluding remarks with a message for everyone to try to help in any way possible others in need.
thoughtsfeels: The story was a good reminder for everyone to appreciate what they have, to embrace the kindness and humanity in others, and to be vigilant and receptive to others who are less fortunate by helping in any way possible.
whydonate: I give multiple times throughout the year to charities that I know and trust and whose mission and values I understand and identify with. I would prefer to use the total bonus amount as an addition to my next anonymous donation.

thoughtsfeels: This is the very sad reality of the world we live in today. Although this story happened in the US, the same situation could easily have happened in the UK, and in fact, is more likely to happen here I believe owing to the demonisation of the poor, disabled and unemployed who constantly face devastating sanctions.
whydonate: I am disabled, and facing the same situation the woman in the story was. I could have been reading about myself, minus the 3 kids, but with 2 cats and a dog. As I wait for my reassessment for PIP, I know I will have my dla denied this time around as the Government is trying to cut the number of claimants. I will be found fit for work, which I am not. It is only a matter of time until my disability forces me to miss a job centre appt. When, not if, that happens, I will be sanctioned and have no income. With no income, I will have no home. At least the woman in the story had her health and could still work. I do not have even that hope.
comments: That one was just a bit too close to home for comfort. However, I genuinely believe that those who have experienced tragedy of some sort are the most likely to help others in their time of need.

brieflydescribe: The woman in the story lost her home, because the landlords couldn't pay their mortgage. The rest of the story was her journey in trying to find a suitable place to stay, and MANY reasons why she couldn't. Her story is full of challenges and shows the crisis that many normal working people face every day.
thoughtsfeels: I found it interesting in the end, that the woman found her friend's two bedroom apartment the most suitable place to stay. I feel mostly sorry for her children, through no fault of their own, they were left in a very unstable situation. I find it interesting that her ex husband was not mentioned at all (if he were not in the same city then it's understandable) but it would have been a great alternative for the children. One thing that drives me crazy is the extent to which pets hinder people... Yet most people LOVE their babies ... Her friend had 3!!! cats, and her brother had dogs (i forgot how many), which rendered these places unstable. The animal's well being because they are part of the family took president over the well being of a HUMAN... Sorry for the rant. In the end I do feel sorry for the woman and her children. I hope she managed to find a place where they could be stable.
whydonate: I DO NOT support charities, especially non-profit corporations. I support local fundraisers for community centres and such, but these massive companies that have executives and offices all over the world have far too much overhead, they end up donating similar amounts of money every corporation does for tax relief.
otherissues: No issues, the loading times were fine and the print was easy to read. Good story and study over all! Thank you for the HIT!
comments: Good story and study. I did enjoy reading the woman's thoughts on her situation.

brieflydescribe: The person's landlord hadn't signed their lease because of financial issues, and the new owners didn't want them to rent - so they had to vacate the house within 4 days. They were unable to find a new home for their family, and were bouncing around between friends, family, and sometimes hotels.
thoughtsfeels: I felt really bad for this situation and how stressful it would have been. I can't imagine how difficult this situation was. But (as the author mentioned), the author was also in this situation from a very privileged position. They had people they could stay with, even if it was far from ideal. They had family that was able to take the kits. They had a car to help vacate the premise. As a result, although I felt bad, I also couldn't help but think that they were in a pretty stable place. They didn't have a place to rent, but they were very, very far from 'homeless'.
whydonate: The thing that struck me about the story was: the author was in a really bad spot, but was quite privileged. The author was in the terrible position where they didn't have a place for their family to rend, but they were not homeless by any stretch. They could afford to stay in a motel some nights, and had friends and family they could stay with. It made me think about how Habitat for Humanity helps people that are in a really tough spot, but often doesn't help the poorest people. Habitat for Humanity does great work, but they tend to help middle-class people who are experiencing loss more than people that are actually homeless. I might just be trying to justify keeping the money, but yesterday I got a $5 gift card for a homeless person that asked me for money. I am in a tough financial spot right now, and have had to stop all non-necessary expenses (like coffee or going out to eat). I thought if I took this money and donated it directly to a homeless person (through a gift card), it would do more to help people that are really poor than donating to Habitat for Humanity.
otherissues: No, everything worked smoothly. Good luck with your research :)!

brieflydescribe: The author lost their rented home because of an unfortunate ownership change. They spent months bouncing around at different friends and family's homes. Finally they got to settle with their three kids at a friend's two bedroom apartment.
thoughtsfeels: I'm currently in a similar situation; I was very sick in January this year and lost my job - and subsequently lost my apartment. I stayed with my girlfriend for a couple weeks, then she broke up with me. Stayed with a friend for a week, then went back to live with my parents for three months. I searched for a job the whole time but found nothing. Now I've moved across the province and am living in a tiny town with a friend kind enough to let me stay here as long as I need. She's helping me settle and find a job, and even helped me start volunteering at the local humane society. If it wasn't for her, I don't know what would have happened to me. My parents aren't interested in having their 23 year old daughter at home, especially since we have many disagreements about my lifestyle choices . I would have had to give up my dog and stay in a shelter if my friend hadn't saved me.
whydonate: I don't really need one dollar THAT badly. Habitat for Humanity is doing important things and if doing a survey can give them a dollar, I'm game.
comments: An interesting one that hits REALLY close to home. I hope my contribution is useful.

brieflydescribe: A single mother lost her rental and had to find a new home. She struggled for several months to find anywhere to rent for herself and her three kids. She stayed in various peoples' homes, including family members and friends. Several times she spent the night in her car. Eventually, she and her family settled in one room in her best college friend_‹_s house. Throughout this ordeal the author discovered who her true friends were. Those who had little offered the most, and those who had a lot offered very little. She also found out how hard it is to find affordable housing within commute distance of her job. The story ended with her settled in the one bedroom, very thankful that she had a spot for her kids to temporarily call home.
thoughtsfeels: I would like to know why she didn_‹_t ask the kids_‹_ father for help.
whydonate: Habitat is a good charity that does great things for the community.

brieflydescribe: After discovering that her landlords had not paid their mortgage in some time and that she would be forcibly evicted from her home in four days time; the main character set out in search of a new home for herself and her three children. Despite her determination and valiant efforts, she was unable to obtain a new permanent address and was forced to live in undesirable conditions along with her children. Although the main character and her children were exposed to a much dimmer reality than what they were used to; they learned to appreciate the few things they did have and to be grateful for those around them who are willing to help.
thoughtsfeels: Treat others as you wish to be treated. It can't hurt to help the less fortunate when you are able because you can never predict when a life altering event will place yourself and perhaps your family in a position in which you require the help of those around you. Always Appreciate the people and things u do have and remember that, although it may not seem like much to you at times, there are others out there that are far less fortunate and have significantly less. Things could always be worse. Don't wait until you've experienced something unfortunate for yourself to lend a helping hand to those in need. But also, Beware. Not all of us are as kind hearted as we may find first appear. Have faith in yourself and be positive thoughts. Have faith, be selfless and keep smiling. Remember, when you're at the bottom, you've no place to go but up!
whydonate: I hope that if ever I am in a similar situation, that someone would do the same for me.

thoughtsfeels: It is a far too common story and one that affects a great many people. It pains the heart to read about that sort of struggle and know that many are living a life this way or with less. This was a story that created a fair amount of empathy and emotion within as i read the chapters.
whydonate: It is right to give to those that need it more than yourself and i am happy to offer what little i can to those that have less than myself or my family. brieflydescribe: A woman and her three children were evicted because new owners bought the rental property. She stayed with friends and relatives, and while she struggled a lot, she eventually found affordable housing.
thoughtsfeels: I thought it was excellent. Well written, and the interactive nature really allows the reader to relate to the protagonist. It really put a face on homelessness. A friend of mine was also on the verge of becoming homeless in a city far from where I live. When I read this story, I thought of my friend and how they talked about housing and support when they were in that situation. Like the protagonist, they have since found affordable housing.
whydonate: Because money is tight for me and I often have a hard time doing things that I feel are important because I need to worry about feeding myself, and rent, and that makes it hard to be able to donate or to volunteer. With this, it wasn't income I was depending on, and in fact, I can only redeem it in Amazon gift cards, so it's not essential money for me and I've volunteered with H4H and they're an amazing organization.
comments: I think you should make that story freely available online. It would probably change a lot of views and end some ignorance about homelessness.

Thankfully, a college friend offered the family a place to stay until they could find one of their own. It just goes to show us all how easily we can move from comfort to homeless in this day and age.
thoughtsfeels: I don't think people in general realize that this story could happen to any number of us who live in lower and even middle class. All it takes is something drastic, like being evicted, to turn lives upside down. The story was well written.
whydonate: I wanted to donate something but have also donated other monies of mine. Also, I am in need of these part-time online gigs to help with my financial situation.
comments: This was a unique type of survey that I have not done before.

brieflydescribe: A woman who had been a good tenant, faithfully paying her rent on time each month, nonetheless found herself suddenly homeless when it turned out that her landlord had not been making his payments on the mortgage. For several months she struggled, trying to find a home for herself and her three kids, but it was very difficult because landlords were taking advantage of the glut of renters in the market and raising the prices. She stayed with family, friends, and in hotels, trying to rotate things so that she did not wear out her welcome in any one place. The story was a description of what happens when someone's life gets upturned through no fault of their own.
thoughtsfeels: I find this sort of story heartbreaking. So many people are precariously close to being in the same situation as this woman yet have no clue. Most people have such a preconceived notion of what it means to be homeless -- the stereotypical dirty street person begging for booze money. But there are so many of the working homeless -- homeless only because they did not have quite enough of a safety net or because one too many unfortunate downturns happen in their lives in too short a period. We don't see the struggle that these people endure. I can't even imagine the stress of trying to make such a change in life as a move like this woman had with all the additional stress of being an unwanted houseguest, the lack of time to accomplish things because work commutes were suddenly immensely longer. I feel very sad now and a little hopeless. I don't know what we've become as a society that we don't want to help more people in this sort of situation.
whydonate: I think that is a good organization to help people like the woman in the story. But I am not in much better shape than she is, so I sort of need the money myself. 50-50 seemed to be the best way for me to split it so that my conscience wouldn't completely make me feel like crap.

brieflydescribe: My eviction did not come with a dramatic pounding on the front door, like it happens in the movies. Just an unceremonious letter, lumped in between credit card offers and credit card bills. It would have been helpful if it had come in the form of a Howler, ê_ la Harry Potter - literally screeching at me that if I was not out by that Friday, me and my belongings would be forcibly removed from the property. Instead the letter that contained my fate masqueraded as an innocent piece of junk mail. When I opened it, the letter let me know I would now start a four-day race to vacate my premises. The whole thing happened the week of July 4. Although my rent had been faithfully paid throughout my entire tenancy, the owners of the town home I had been renting for the past three years had not paid their mortgage in at least a third of that time. After a series of frantic phone calls (property management company, Real Estate Commission, and the sheriff's department), I had determined a few unfortunate things. Because the owner - knowing of this impending doom - had delayed signing my new lease, I had little to no protection. The new owners were under no obligation to rent to me. No lease, no luck. I still had to work that week. And longstanding plans for my three children to attend a family reunion with my ex-in-laws meant I would lose another crucial day to pack, plan and allow myself a small cushion of time for general freak-outs. I got the kids ready and drove them halfway between North Carolina and Pennsylvania. By the time I got home, I was exhausted from the eight-hour trip and wanted nothing more than to curl up in a ball and slip into a temporary coma. But the real work was just beginning. Now I had to figure out how to pack all my belongings in just a few short days.

brieflydescribe: A single parent with several children was evicted after the landlord failed to keep up on the mortgage. The family became homeless; while the parent kept a job, the family bounced from place to place. After staying at the parent's mother's house, among other spots, they were finally taken in by the parent's best friend from college.
thoughtsfeels: I felt great sympathy and empathy for the protagonist in this story. Many of us with homes take it for granted that we will always have a safe, comfortable place to live. However, at any moment, our homes could be ripped out from under us. This story emphasizes the difficulty of finding housing without access to the appropriate resources. I have always been a champion of affordable housing, and I wish that more governmental money could be allocated to this important concern. This way, everyone would be able to live safely and happliy.
whydonate: I feel that affordable housing is important for everyone to have, and every little bit helps. I appreciate and value Habitat for Humanity. Additionally, I am new to Amazon Mechanical Turk, and so I am fine with receiving lower compensation for my novice efforts.
otherissues: Everything worked fine. Thanks for my first survey on Amazon Mechanical Turk, and have a lovely day! :)
comments: Thank you very much. Surveys are fun! :D

brieflydescribe: The protagonist has become homeless due to their landlord's financial incompetence. The protagonist sends his family away in attempts to locate a house for his/her's family, networking with friends, family and coworkers to little or no avail. Finally, after months (if not maybe years) of struggle, the Protagonist's best friend from college (and family) give shelter, normalcy and the security of a home for his family.
thoughtsfeels: I do feel some empathy or compassion for the Protagonist, but I feel as though they might be a little too judgmental about their living conditions (i.e criticizing his sister's HELLISHLY hot apartment or allergy to cats). You're homeless, I get it, but really, you SHOULD be making the best of it and bite the bullet; stop bitching and pick up your bootstraps and go endeavour to be the best for your family. Stay in a home that's too hot, bear with some allergies for crying out loud. A one and a half hour drive to your job is acceptable if you have no home. Be more pragmatic and a little less focused on the negative physical location you are in. The emotion was palpable at times throughout the story and quite sad. The story truly felt as though it is/were real (I mean this moreso in the style of writing and delivery).
whydonate: My current financial status/condition is not fit enough to be able to donate funds to an organization I know nothing about (i.e where its funding goes etc).
comments: Very interesting and thought provoking, but a tad too long

brieflydescribe: The mother was renting from owners who were not paying their mortgage even though she was paying her rent to them. This left she and her 3 children homeless with no where to go. The mother let her children stay with their grandmother while they were homeless and the mother looked for a place to stay. The mother had to drive from city to city staying with relatives, friends and in hotels while trying to stay close to her job. Then, her best friend allowed the whole family to stay in their spare bedroom until she could get on her feet.
thoughtsfeels: Ironically, I have read this story before because I have googled how people become homeless. I have technically been homeless for the past years living in a Motel due to several bad choices, my boyfriend being a sex-offender, and a terrible addiction to crack which I am trying to battle daily. I have also stayed in a rooming house/boarding home for a year when I quit my job without having another one which was the stupidest thing I have ever done. So I kind of know what it is like to be barely homeless and feel like you have no stable place to live and it really sucks. I feel so bad for what this mother went through having to worry about her 3 children on top of finding a place to live. This is one of the worst situations anyone can through and I would never wish homelessness on anyone.
whydonate: I chose that amount because it is a fair amount to donate leaving me with a reward for my work as well.
comments: yes, the hit expired before I could finish and I'm upset about this because I put a lot of effort into this hit.

brieflydescribe: Someone was evicted from their home with only a few days notice. They had faithfully paid their rent, but the owners had not paid their mortgage. This left this person suddenly homeless. This person has children and went through many struggles staying with friends and family while continuing to work. New housing was very hard to come by. At the end, no permanent solution had been found, but they were in a place slightly more stable for the time.
thoughtsfeels: I think more care should have been taken originally with the rental so that the loophole mentioned wouldn't have left this person in such a predicament. Is housing that difficult to find? Can't they find a fixer upper? I've lived in the south during summer for many years, some years without AC, and it is doable though not enjoyable. That brings into question are they being too picky? Why isn't the ex contributing financially for a home for all these children? Makes me think there's more to the story. Sometimes (not always) people contribute to their own problems.
whydonate: Because of my Biblical beliefs, I do not fully support Habitat for Humanity. It is based on improving the world by improving people's circumstances. Although this isn't bad , I would much rather support missionaries who take the gospel to people. And, my family supports missionaries monthly. Changing one's heart is more important than changing their circumstances.
otherissues: Story was basically logical in sequence. Almost checked yes above because: The main character mentioned sharing bunk with children at the point in the story they were still with ex's family. Not a problem, later it became clear they were all together after that visit.

brieflydescribe: The author received an unexpected eviction notice through no fault of his/her own and was forced to try to find a new place to live almost immediately. Fortunately, his/her kids were away for awhile, but the cushion of time did not really help. By the time the children came back, the author had stayed night-to-night in a variety of places, continuing to work all the while but with no permanent home. Ultimately, s/he was taken in by his/her ex-roomate and husband, who didn't have much room but were willing to share what they did have. This allowed a sense of normalcy to return to the family and very much instilled the author with a sense of gratitude and advise to other to help those in need.
thoughtsfeels: This is quite an emotional story. The part about hearing people's have you tried this 's really resonated. I am sort of in that situation with another issue, and it makes me crazy and put on the defensive to explain why this or that didn't work. Ultimately, I find that's where my energy goes, and it's just easier to avoid communicating with them altogether until I can get things turned around... But anyway... after reading this, I was left with a really good feeling about people helping people and how we should all not be so quick to judge people who may be having a much harder time of things than we could possibly imagine.
whydonate: I really need money and do not even make a living wage at the moment. Giving this payment to Habitat won't kill me. It just means I need to try to take another survey. In addition, people who are eligible for Habitat have undoubtedly had a more difficult life than I have, and if something as tiny as this small donation helps them get even a little closer to their goal of having their own home, that's meaningful.
otherissues: Not that I can think of.

brieflydescribe: This story is about a parent whom gets kicked out of his/her apartment due to his/her landlord not paying the rent off. Then they hop from place to place trying to find somewhere to get back on their feet without being too far from their job. In the end, one of their crazy friends helps them out and they become eternally grateful for everything.
thoughtsfeels: Actually, I can completely relate to this story. Over the past six months I've had nowhere to go. My girlfriend and I have been traveling and living on the streets trying to find a place to go. I have traveled from Virginia all of the way to Southern California on foot(no car). We slept in nooks and crannies everywhere getting hassled by business owners and police. We were just scrapping by literally dumpster diving for food and hopping in the ocean for showers. This story was completely enjoyable for me because it's very similar to what I went through except I just had my girlfriend to take care of instead of three children.
whydonate: I chose the amount I did because I have been in situation like this myself. I remember absolutely nobody would help me and my girlfriend. It took us over a year before we were able to even get halfway on my feet. In fact, I'm still homeless. Fortunately, I'm able to stay with a couple family members for the time being. However, I feel like some people need it more than I do so that's why I'm going to donate 50%. I need to help others but at the same time I need to help myself.
comments: I loved this story. It was absolutely touching and I am so happy that you all are doing that for others. I try to help out anyway I can. My story is so much similar you have no idea,in fact, I'm still sort of in that situation. Thank you guys for giving me such an enjoyable hit.

brieflydescribe: The author was evicted from his townhome because the old owners/landlords had failed to pay the mortgage and also had not signed a new lease with him, so when the new owners bought the townhome they were under no obligation to allow the author to continue living there. After moving out, the author bounced around to various motels, apartments, and houses of strangers, friends, and family members; his 3 children luckily were able to stay with their grandparents for awhile but eventually had to come back to live with their dad. The author has been unable to find a new place for he and his children to live because he can't afford to purchase a home and is having an extremely difficult time finding affordable rentals (and those he does find he cannot get because landlords are extremely picky about tenants given the increased demand for rentals by renters and the fact that he is a single parent with three children on a fixed income).
thoughtsfeels: While I wish I could say this narrative is surprising, it is not at all. I feel for the author and his children and all of the other people and/or families that find themselves in this exact situation. I myself have had to deal with finding an apartment in a market that has less than 1% availability. Like the author said, landlords are extremely picky about who they will rent to and as a younger 20-something, even with a perfect rental history, I am not at the top of their list of people to rent to. Many of my friends have had to resort to having multiple roommates (even in their late 20s and early to mid-30s) because of the high cost of rent in cities in the US. Others must still get their parents to cosign for them because they alone (even gainfully employed) do not meet the minimum income requirements for renters. I cannot imagine this scenario if I had 3 young children to take care of; I can't even begin to comprehend the stress that this causes the author of this story. What do you even tell your children? And having to rely on friends, family members, strangers, or resorting to staying in motels and hotels, constantly couch-surfing and moving around while having to work full-time would be so awful. Unfortunately, stories like this one are far too common in the US today. However, the one saving grace for the author is that he has supportive people in his life. Some people and their families would not be so lucky and would end up in a homeless shelter, on the streets, or living out of a car. That is not to negate his experience as I can sympathize and empathize with the struggle he and his family are facing.
whydonate: I am unemployed and need every penny I can get. However, I have volunteered for Habitat for Humanity in the past and my family has donated money to them on several occasions.

thoughtsfeels: I thought this was an interesting piece because it highlights the ease with which someone can become homeless. This was not the story of a person who squandered their money or had reckless spending habits, but a normal single-parent who had an unfortunate circumstance thrust upon them.
whydonate: I can afford to give some.

brieflydescribe: Sidebar, I understand this poor woman. A woman with children becomes homeless through not fault of her own. Her mortgage holder didn't do what he/she was supposed to do, and she ended up receiving an eviction notice which wasn't even properly served! Who sends an eviction notice through the mail?? She moves from place to place and ends up with her college friend, her college friends husband, and their new baby...sleeping with her children in their spare bedroom.
thoughtsfeels: I felt her pain even though throughout the reading I also knew how fortunate she was. I raised 6 children a single mother and we because virtually homeless. I have no other family, and we were in a very precarious position until I got back on my feet!!
whydonate: It's what I do. I have had a very hard life so I want to give even though I'm still struggling. It feels good and it's the right thing to do!!

brieflydescribe: The author became homeless through no fault of her own, and had to rely on the kindness of her friends and family in order to keep going. She describes the difficulties and frustrations associated with her situation, while expressing her understanding that things could have been even worse, were it not for the support from her loved ones.
thoughtsfeels: The story made me somewhat sad, but more angry. Though the story occurs in the United States and I have never lived there, I remain angered and disappointed in the lack of provisions made for people in need, a housing bubble which has been almost entirely forgotten, and the disdain all too frequently expressed towards people trying to cope with hard times.
whydonate: I'm poor and I need the money
comments: Overall it was quite a pleasant experience, and the story was genuinely interesting and moving to read, it was a good choice.

brieflydescribe: The story provides us an insight into the struggles of an evicted single mother who is trying to find a home. We see how uncomfortable being homeless actually is and how feeling like a burden is uncomfortable and awkward to move from home to home in search of a roof on top of their heads.
thoughtsfeels: The story is heartbreaking and one can really empathise with her struggle, however (unfortunately) situations like these are very common and without additional support for single mothers it can be very tough out there. Her situation certainly was difficult, however I felt more at ease knowing she had friends and family to support her, even though it was uncomfortable, because some people don't even have family etc. So in that sense she is lucky. I chose mother first in all situations because the mother in my opinion is the most supportive figure usually.
whydonate: It is a small amount, but not too small in contrast to the payment for the survey. I'm sure if everyone chipped in, it will add up and help.
comments: I think this survey was great. It was entertaining and emotional, also incorporating an opportunity to help those in that situation was an excellent idea, well done. I hope a lot of people donate.

brieflydescribe: A single mother of three becomes homeless when her landlords default on their payments. She struggles to find an affordable place in an inflated housing market and is forced to live in her car and hop from couch to couch of people she knows. She finally manages to find a constant in her life thanks to her best friend and best friend's husband who offer shelter in their modest apartment.
thoughtsfeels: It feels like a very relatable story, one that strikes too close to home, especially after the housing crash ten years back. I think the working class can identify with the struggles of a person who is out of options but also wants to maintain some routine and self-respect.
whydonate: I am unfortunately not in a position to be giving money away (though I do realize this is missing the point of the story). I simply lack the financial and job security to feel comfortable donating money to others.
storyoff_what: The ending seemed abrupt. Out of nowhere, her friend and friend's husband's home suddenly is ok for her family to live at.

brieflydescribe: A working, single mother of three became homeless with little forewarning and spent a few months trying to find affordable new accommodation for her and her children. When this proved difficult, she was left with no other choice but to stay with friends, her mother, and even sleep in the car. This continued for longer than she had imagined it would; she devised many techniques to avoid being an inconvenience for those she stayed with. Eventually an old college friend and her husband offered their spare room to her and her children with no strings attached which she is very grateful for.
thoughtsfeels: I found it a very well written personal account of homelessness. It shows that even those who are working can only have enough to get by on, especially single parents with children, and it is therefore hard to save for this kind of event. I do have good hope for her in that she is resilient and intelligent, and has friends and family who have helped her. She may be overly thoughtful of others though and should put herself first and pursue what it takes to become more financially sound.
whydonate: I have lost faith in how much money I donate to charities actually gets to the vulnerable people who need it which is why I donate as directly as possible to people rather than through a middle party. 10% I feel is a high percentage to give on that basis. If I met this lady myself I would give it all to her.
comments: I am new to mturk but this is the first time I have seen a survey addressing homelessness in any way.

brieflydescribe: A parent was evicted from their home because their landlord hadn't paid their mortgage and the new landlord didn't want them as a tenant, leaving the person homeless. They scrambled around for a while trying to find a place to stay but never found a permanent home. They relied on friends and family members to find a place to stay, but they had to jump around a lot, and their kids had trouble finding stability.
thoughtsfeels: My main thoughts are about how something like this could happen to me. I live in a precarious situation as well, and I could easily see myself not having a place to stay, just like the author. I was also thinking about how pathetic it is that in this country, the wealthiest country in the world, many people are still unable to find a place to sleep at night. It's just very sad.
whydonate: I didn't want to donate 0% since that would feel wrong. I would have preferred to keep it all, honestly, but I just didn't feel right not donating anything.
comments: I can't think of anything else.

brieflydescribe: Through no fault of her own, the lady and her children became homeless. The system let them down terribly, offering no assistance in their time of need. Only the extreme generosity of a good friend saved them from ending up in a homeless shelter, or on the streets.
thoughtsfeels: Having been homeless myself, I can identify very well with this story. Despite what the mainstream media, and most people, would have us believe, this sort of thing can, and often does, happen to any of us. If it does happen to you, you will quickly find out just how 'good' your good friends are, and how extremely sympathetic complete strangers can be.
whydonate: Because people need, and deserve to be helped when in difficulty, and the onus is on society as a whole to do just that. When you find yourself more fortunate than others, it is better to build a longer table than a higher wall.

brieflydescribe: The author became homeless after her landlord's home was foreclosed and the new owners would not renew the lease. The author then struggled to find a new living situation. The author is also a single mother with 3 children which added an additional complexity to her homeless situation.
thoughtsfeels: I felt particularly moved that the person who the author felt most connected with on a personal level during her homelessness was her friend who she felt had the least ability to help her. I have found through my own personal struggles that this is often the case, that individuals who have the least often have the most grace and willingness to support others. The author's family tried and were willing to support her, which I also felt was amazing, they just were not able to give her the support she needed. I did think she was a little picky about some of these situations. I understand that with children you occasionally need to be, again through my own personal experiences, however she seemed to be overly concerned about some of the smaller details about her sister's and brother's living situations.
whydonate: If I was being paid a bonus, it is not money that I was expecting to receive and I believe in giving back to the community.

brieflydescribe: The narrator became suddenly homeless after her landlord failed to pay the mortgage for a period of time. The narrator sent her children to family for a while, as previously planned, and embarked on packing and moving out of their home, then going through a lengthy period of moving from temporary places to stay with family and friends, sometimes even staying in her old car, all of which she appreciated, although they all had drawbacks. During this period she continued work and looked for a place to call home, but realized how difficult this has become lately.
thoughtsfeels: I found this story very moving, especially so for its realism tempered with a bit of tongue-in-cheek humor. It definitely rings true, and is a sad indictment of what probably happens on a daily basis in hundreds of places throughout this country. As the author pointed out, there are many people who live permanently homeless and hopeless. The author did a great job of telling her painful story in such a way as to educate others who have not been in that situation as to the many problems and pains encountered by those who become or are suddenly homeless, eliciting empathy and an awareness that there are not sufficient resources provided for those in this situation.
whydonate: I chose not to donate because I already donate to charities in other ways, and am currently on an extremely limited, fixed income.
comments: I greatly enjoyed this story and survey. The format, allowing for participation to steer the narrative, was original, creative, and well done, and the story itself was very well written, educational and elicited empathy, understanding, and a new appreciation for the relative security I have.

brieflydescribe: A woman who faithfully paid her bills got evicted from her place because others were not paying their bills next door. She had no where else to go and stayed with family and friends and in her car while still going to work. Eventually her best friend and best friend's husband let them stay at their small place and they are grateful and the woman who was evicted says we should all help out when we can.
thoughtsfeels: I think it is very sad. I think we should all help out. I get my empathy from my mom and my giving qualities from my dad. My dad has given so much to neighbors and his coworkers who he managers and has helped pay their medical bills or get them medicine when they needed it. He has given money to family in emergencies (large sums which sometimes upsets me but he looks out for those he loves). I have helped people in the past by giving them what they need during hard times or have helped them with a temporary place to stay as well (when I was in college I let a friend who I made that year who was from Peru come stay at my Mom's for a very cheap monthly price of 150.00 each month compared to where he was staying before but then had to go). I want to continue to help out because it is what God would want us to do and so much has been given to me- food, a roof over my head, and love from family and friends.
whydonate: I would like to give some to help out a little. I would also like to keep some for me to save up for my wedding next year.

brieflydescribe: The woman in the story was evicted, with her three children, because her landlord did not pay their mortgage. It left she and her three children without a home with only 4 days notice. The rest of the story talks about how she has to scramble to try and find a home with little to no money, how this makes she and her family feel.
thoughtsfeels: I have been involved with the homeless population in many ways over the last 20 years. My heart is with them as many have unfortunate circumstances they must over come. Last year I began a Toastmasters club with 40 men from the orlando union rescue mission. Today I have 20-30 active members at any one time. It is completely free for them. It gives them a chance to overcome by accident and learn from each other. It is an invisible support group and it is a normal social outlet for them in which we have many visitors. In 5 short months we chartered the club. One member won speech contests and was one position away from be an international contestant. This is truly the best day and hour of my entire week! thoughtsfeels: Interesting story. I liked the availability of options to choose which way the story would be told. It evoked in me feelings of pity for the homeless man, especially when his kid wrote about the homelessness on a cardboard paper. brieflydescribe: A renter became homeless because the owner's lost ownership of the property and did not sign the rental lease to allow the renter to stay under new ownership. As a result of these circumstances, the renter becomes homeless and seeks alternative solutions to housing such as staying with a best friend, sister, brother, mother, or in the car. However, the best living arrangement was staying at the best friend's home, which provided a sense of normalcy despite all of the chaos involved with finding a place to call home.
thoughtsfeels: This was an interesting story because it really depicts what homeless people encounter. Also, there are many preconceived notions regarding why a person has become homeless. Sometimes an individual becomes homeless and is a responsible individual who is trying to provide for his or her family. Furthermore, I think it was important to state that everyone should be treated with dignity. People who are homeless should be given respect and dignity to help boost their confidence that they will overcome their struggle.
whydonate: I really need the bonus, but I thought I could sacrifice 50% of the bonus to Habitat for Humanity. I know that they provide homes for people who do not have housing.

brieflydescribe: A person becomes homeless through no fault of their own. They struggle to find the help they need with finding a new place. After exhausting their options with family members, they are eventually able to stay with a friend.
thoughtsfeels: The story saddens me because I know there are many families who go through this very situation. Unfortunately, the issue with low-paying/minimum wage jobs does not help anything. The idea that the majority of people flipping burgers somewhere are teens is incredibly false. There are plenty of adults working to support their families who may end up in the situation described in the story because of unreasonably low pay. I feel sorry for the kids in this story as well. It can be incredibly hard to focus on your education or making friends when you don't even know where you'll be living in a couple weeks.
whydonate: The truth is, as much as I want to help people too, there isn't much I can afford to give up right now. I'm not quite on the verge of homelessness, but I am also not what you would describe as completely financially secure. Fifty cents may not seem like a lot, but if every person who took the survey chose to donate part of their $1, it would surely add up. I donate money when I can to causes that are important to me. If more people chose to donate just a little bit when they can, many charitable causes would be able to make an even bigger difference for the people who need it most.
otherissues: I did not witness other issues with the story or the survey.
comments: The option to donate to Habitat for Humanity immediately after reading about someone becoming homeless is very well-planned out. I sincerely hope you see a lot of people donate at least a little bit of the dollar.

brieflydescribe: A single parent lost her rented home when her landlord failed to pay his mortgage. She was able to let her 3 children stay with their grandparents for a month in the summer while she looked for new housing but ultimately she was unable to find anything and the family of four was forced to stay with family and friends for months while she looked for new housing. The poor housing market and her personal situation made it almost impossible for her to find affordable housing and the family remained homeless for many months.
thoughtsfeels: I felt bad for the mother and her children. The children must have been very confused about their situation and mother must have been very depressed and full of stress. It is hard enough to raise 3 children and work full-time without having to worry about not having a place to live. This is something that many of us take for granted everyday - having a place to go home to. I was a little confused as to why she was having such a hard time finding SOMETHING to rent. I have a hard time imagining that finding some kind of rental for a someone with a steady job and income seemed so impossible for such a long time.
whydonate: I don't think a dollar would do much help someone else build a house and this survey took a while to complete.

brieflydescribe: The lady's landlords failed to pay their mortgage, and so, in the foreclosure, she was evicted. For months, she relied on the generosity of family and friends to provide overnight accommodation for her and her three children.
thoughtsfeels: This is a common story in a world of growing population numbers. It throws into focus the question of the rights the state should have to impel property owners to use their property in a particular way - something which to most western states is going to be a very fraught debate, given the respect there has always been for the rights of owners over their own property. The housing crises in various countries are also helping fuel class and racial tensions.
whydonate: The story did remind me how fortunate I am and how awful homelessness is - and how awful in different ways, by which I mean it is one type of experience for the kids; another several types for the mother; but it also impacts on those who felt honour-bound to try and help them, even at the cost of inconvenience to their own lives.
condition_other: story, choices, option to donate, further questions and then this (apparently final) section

brieflydescribe: A woman was evicted from her home due to her landlord not making payments, despite her rents being on time, and she wasn't protected due to the landlord not signing the lease. Because of this, the woman and her three children had to live with grandparents, friends, get help from strangers, stay in an old car, etc. The mother spent months working while struggling to find a home for her three children before school started, and she didn't get that until her best friend and her husband offered her a place to stay.
thoughtsfeels: This story was extremely long and it was on a computer screen, which intimidated me initially. However, as I kept reading, I got engrossed into the tale and the woman and her children's rough patch. I couldn't stop reading because I was so invested in their struggle and perseverance that it gave me the will to continue reading, just so I could know what happened to them in the end. I was very moved and inspired by this woman's misfortune and how she stuck it through and rose from it.
whydonate: I chose to not donate anything because if I wanted to donate to this cause, I would certainly donate more than $1. I'll rather donate money myself and know the money was being given by me than give someone else the go ahead to donate my money. It just makes me feel better donating on a more intimate and personal level, than depending on the internet.
otherissues: None that I know of, so thank you for allowing me to participate in your study because I never expected to enjoy it and be as involved into the study and the story as much as I was.
comments: Thank you for allowing me to participate in this survey, and I hope my responses were of use to you.

brieflydescribe: I was being evicted on very short notice without the renewal of my lease. I went from place to place try to find somewhere to go with my 3 children. I tried family, friends and hotels. Only to find that most people unless absolutely necessary would be willing to help me. But in the end I was taken in by a family with 2 bedrooms and a newborn. They showed us kindness and made us feel as if we were at home.
thoughtsfeels: I have been in a similar predicament myself. I went through a horrible divorce and found myself not only homeless, thinking I had lost my job and not even a car. My husband stopped paying my bills while I was in the hospital dying. I was in the hospital for over 9 weeks and he came to visit me only twice the entire time. When I got out of the hospital I was left with only 50.00 in my account. Luckily in the hospital I met an amazing person that sent me on a path that not only did I receive Jesus in my heart. I got my job back and found a place that I could walk to and from work everyday. I did this for an entire year and I have learned so many life lessons along the way. I to had no one to turn to family, friends no one except God.
whydonate: I am willing to give half of what I earned to help others.
otherissues: I found the story very captivating and the more I read the more I was able to get into the character, especially since I could relate to a degree. Thank you for allowing me to participate in this study. I enjoyed doing it and hope my answers are helpful.
comments: Thank you for allowing me to participate.

brieflydescribe: The storyteller was evicted for no fault of their own and had no time to find a new place to live. They put all their stuff in storage, took their kids to a family reunion and left them with their grandparents (in Texas?) while they returned to search for a home. They were unable to find one and traveled from house to house and between cities relying on friends and relatives who allowed them to stay for short periods of timein spare rooms or (in the case of the mother, their only room. Some of the homes they stayed in were too far from work, others had no air conditioning, cats, or a new baby. They spent the entire time anxious, and failed to find a new home before the children had to return for school. They had no idea where the children were even going to go for school because they had no address.
thoughtsfeels: It's a heartbreaking story. Being homeless is horrible. Staying with relatives when you are not welcome is horrible, and you end up bending over backwards to try and make yourself welcome while also living with the knowledge that you will have nowhere to go if they decide they have had enough of your presence. It is horrible to know your children are suffering and there is nothing you can do about it.
whydonate: Because no one should be homeless, especially children and no one should have to live somewhere they are not wanted. I know sort of what this feels like because when we sold our house and moved in with my mother, it took much longer to get a house than we expected and we just barely managed get one only a few days before the date she chose to kick us out. She chose Easter as the deadline, and we signed the contract for our house on tax day. None of us cared about celebrating Easter by the time is came because wewere all horribly depressed. Habitat for Humanity is a good charity that helps a lot of people. I would give them more if I could, but I'm afraid we are going to lose our house in the near future as well. My brother in law used to build houses with them so I am well aware of what they do.
Occupation_otherwhat: On SSDI and supplementing that income with Mechanical turk. Also looking for a way to get a job that I can do, so I can get off disability because it does not pay enough.
