brieflydescribe: A single parent with three children was evicted from their home because the owner of the home had not paid their mortgage and had lost it as a result. The parent spent months looking for a new place to live, going from place to place and staying wherever they could, which was not as difficult while the children were with family but became harder when they returned. Eventually a friend from college and her husband allowed them to stay in their spare room, giving the evicted family a home and room to breathe.
thoughtsfeels: I felt a lot of sympathy for the person in the story as it is hard living with the uncertainty of having nowhere to stay, even as a single person. The anxiety and stress of having to do it with three children is almost unimaginable. Although I understand the limited help offered by 'friends', I find it terrible that people would let someone that they know go without a roof over their head when they have a way, however small, to help. Yes, I know it happens - I just can't imagine doing that to someone that I called 'friend'. Hopefully the author eventually found a place of their own.
whydonate: I already donate to charity and choose the charities that I donate to carefully. I am far less likely to donate to ANY charity if I feel that I was being manipulated into doing so, as seemed to be the case here. This is not 'spare cash' that I am working for - it is money to keep a roof over my head and food on my table.

brieflydescribe: A mother (I assume it was a woman) becomes homeless with her 3 children. She searches for a place to live but can't find one. Friends and family help out by letting them stay on couches and spare rooms, but they all increasingly suffer emotionally from being displaced and having no stability.
thoughtsfeels: This story really hit home because my (single) mother and I became homeless when I was 15. We had to pack as much as we could fit in her very beat up old car and sit in our local council office until they could find somewhere for us to stay. We stayed in an ancient hotel with peeling wallpaper for a couple of weeks, then were transferred to a homeless hostel where I had to sleep on a creaky uncomfortable pop-up bed which looked and sounded decades old. In total we were homeless for 6 months before we were given a council house (UK social housing scheme). I understand completely what both the narrator and the children were feeling in the story. It brings back a lot of unpleasant memories.
whydonate: To be completely honest, despite now having a roof over my head it's by no means entirely secure as I have a genetic condition which severely inhibits my life (EDS) and have to rely on benefits from the government to get by, which can be (and have been once before) reduced or taken away at any time, leaving me homeless again at a moment's notice. I would love to give the whole amount to the charity, but the reason I'm doing these surveys is to save up enough vouchers for a certain store to eventually be able to buy a wheelchair or mobility scooter, because having that would greatly improve my daily life which at the moment is very limited. I sincerely wish I could help other people in similar circumstances, but to do that I need to get to a place in my life where I'm stable enough to be able to get at least a part time job and have the income to do it. I hope you don't think too badly of my reasons for giving so small an amount. If there is anything else I can do besides donate money please do let me know. Thank you.
Occupation_otherwhat: Unable to work due to illness.
otherissues: No issues, I thought the story was very well written and to the point. I enjoyed the writing style despite the subject matter being a little sad.
comments: This was a very different survey and one which really hit home for me personally as I've experienced the events in the story in my own life. I hope my responses are useful to your project. Thank you very much for letting me participate and I wish you all the best. Thanks.
